description: Order on Artificial Intelligence entered on 6/8/2023: ORDERED that any submission in a case assigned to Judge Vaden that contains text drafted with the assistance of a generative artificial intelligence program on the basis of natural language prompts, including but not limited to ChatGPT and Google Bard, must be accompanied by: (1) A disclosure notice that identifies the program used and the specific portions of text that have been so drafted; (2) A certification that the use of such program has not resulted in the disclosure of any confidential or business proprietary information to any unauthorized party; and it is further ORDERED that, following the filing of such notice, any party may file with the Court any motion provided for by statute or the Rules of the Court of International Trade seeking any relief the party believes the facts disclosed warrant. SO ORDERED. (SEE ORDER FOR FULL DETAILS) (Chien, Jason) (Entered: 06/08/2023)

ORAL ORDER: In the letters at Dkt. Nos. 184, 186, and 189, the parties dispute whether the defendants should be compelled to produce the passenger name record ("PNR") codes associated with Ryanair flights purchased using the defendants' platforms. The court will grant the request to compel production of the PNR codes. Those PNR codes may be viewed by two employees selected by the defendants from the list of five employees identified by Ryanair. Those two employees may use the PNR codes only to determine whether and to what extent Ryanair suffered technical losses as a result of the defendants' actions. The PNR codes may not be used by the Ryanair employees for any other purpose, including but not limited to contacting the customers who booked flights through the defendants' platforms, preventing those customers from booking flights in the future, incorporating the data into a machine learning or artificial intelligence algorithm, or accessing the data for any purpose other than determining the amount of technical harm incurred by Ryanair as a result of the defendants' actions. Signed by Judge William C. Bryson on 7/21/2023. (dds) (Entered: 07/21/2023)

ORDER TO SHOW CAUSE WHY ACTION SHOULD NOT BE DISMISSED PURSUANT TO 28 U.S.C. ยง 1915(e)(2)(B). On December 18, 2019, plaintiff filed a pro se complaint against a large number of defendants including without limitation the FCC, RCA, the Department of Agriculture, the EPA, Artificial Intelligence Satellites, BET, ESPN, Green Giant, and B&M Baked Beans. Most of the complaint is devoted to a listing of the names of different persons and entities without any specific facts to show what they did to violate plaintiff's rights. The complaint otherwise alleges acts of home invasion and bodily assault without additional details. Even affording the complaint a liberal interpretation, it appears that the complaint does not allege sufficient facts to give rise to plausible grounds for relief. Plaintiff shall file a response to this order to show cause by January 13, 2020. It is so ordered. Show Cause Response due by 1/13/2020 Signed by Judge Jeffrey A. Meyer on 12/30/2019.(Gutierrez, Y.) (Entered: 12/30/2019)
